Bay Wheels Analysis¶

by Sarina Chen¶

Data overview¶

I will investigate the Bay Wheels system data publicly available on Lyft's website. Lyft is America's second biggest ride-sharing company, and since last year, the company started offering bike-share and then scooter-share. Their bike sharing network was called Ford GoBike in the San Francisco Bay Area (originally by the service company Motivate which got acquired by Lyft) until Lyft rebranded them as Lyft.

Questions¶

This is based on data from January 2018 to September 2019 in San Francisco city only.

  1. Who are the users?
  2. When do the users ride the most?
  3. Where do the users ride the most?

Who are the users?¶

sns.countplot(data = df, x = "user_type", color = sns.color_palette()[0]);

plt.xlabel("User Type");
plt.ylabel("Trip Count");

# Create annotations
locs, labels = plt.xticks();# get the current tick locations and labels
user_counts = df['user_type'].value_counts()
# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = user_counts[label.get_text()]
    print("There are " + str(count) + " trips taken by " + label.get_text() + "s.");
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/df.shape[0])
    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count-200000, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'w')

There are 2150716 trips taken by Subscribers.
There are 415802 trips taken by Customers.

Since January 2018, there have been 2,150,716 trips taken by Subscribers and 415,802 trips taken by Customers in San Francisco. Subscribers represent 84% of the user base.

The 25th percentile shows 28 years old and 75th percentile shows 38 years old. The majority of bike riders are in their late 20s to 30s. The younger population of users are 15 to 25 years old, while the older population is 40 to 50 years old.

When do the users ride the most?¶

What is the typical time for bike rides?¶

In [20]:
# What time of day are trips taken?
p = df[df.user_type=="Subscriber"].groupby("start_hour").count().reset_index()
plt.plot("start_hour", "bike_id", data=p);
p = df[df.user_type=="Customer"].groupby("start_hour").count().reset_index()
plt.plot("start_hour", "bike_id", data=p);
plt.legend(["Subscriber","Customer"]);
plt.title("Distribution of Bike Rides during the Day", size = 16);
plt.yticks([50000,100000,150000,200000,250000],["50K","100K","150K","200K","250K"]);
plt.ylabel("Number of Users");
plt.xticks([0,5,10,15,20],["12a","5a","10a","3p","8p"]);
plt.xlabel("Time");

The majority of bike rides happen at 9a and 5p for both subscribers and customers. This hints at users taking bikes to travel to work. This pattern makes sense for subscribers who have a significant spike in the number of bike rides during rush hour times.

What day of the week do most people ride?¶

Since most bikers are probably commuters, I would expect most subscribers to ride on weekdays due to the 9a-5p work pattern.

In [32]:
# What day of week are trips taken?
p = df[df.user_type=="Subscriber"].groupby("start_weekday").count().reset_index()
plt.plot("start_weekday", "bike_id", data=p);
p = df[df.user_type=="Customer"].groupby("start_weekday").count().reset_index()
plt.plot("start_weekday", "bike_id", data=p);
plt.legend(["Subscriber","Customer"]);
plt.title("Distribution of Bike Rides throughout the Week", size = 16);
plt.yticks([1e5,2e5,3e5,4e5],["100K","200K","300K","400K"]);
plt.ylim(0,450000);
plt.ylabel("Number of Users");
plt.xticks([1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7],["Mon","Tue","Wed","Thu","Fri","Sat","Sun"]);
plt.xlabel("Day of Week");

As expected, the number of rides by subscribers is significantly more on weekdays than weekends. Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays have the most rides as they are in the middle of the work week. Subscribers tend to have less rides on Mondays and Fridays in case of a long weekend.

Customers have a steadier number of rides throughout the week. While some could be commuters who inconsistently take bike rides, I am guessing that the majority are people exploring the city due to the small increase on Saturday.

There is seasonality involved in bike rides, as winter has significanltly less rides. This could be due to cold and windy weather or people going on winter vacation. The majority of rides happens in August for cusomters, who are likely tourists.

The most trips take around 15 minutes. The average is slightly under 15 minutes. This range is probably the sweet spot for the bikeshare business.

How many miles apart are the destinations?¶

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])
df.distance.hist(grid = False, bins = np.arange(0,6.5,.25));
plt.title("Trip Distance");
plt.xlabel("Distance (miles)");
plt.ylabel("Number of Rides");

Most bike rides approximate 1 mile, while the majority of trips don't stop at stations over 4 miles apart. This is likely a threshold for people to consider other modes of transportation, such as bus, metro, or rideshare.

Are distance and duration correlated?¶

In [87]:
p = df[~(df.duration_sec.isnull()) & ~(df.distance.isnull())]
p["duration_minutes"] = p.apply(lambda x: x.duration_sec/60, axis=1)
plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])
plt.scatter(data=p, x="duration_minutes",y="distance", alpha=.1);
plt.xscale("log");
plt.xlabel("Duration (minutes)");
plt.ylabel("Distance (miles)");
plt.title("Distance by Duration");
plt.xticks([1, 10, 100, 1000],[1, 15, 180, 1800]);

Distance and Duration seem positively correlated until the trip reaches the 15 minute mark.

Like the previous analysis, most rides occur under 4 miles. Rides take longer time the farther the user travels, until after a certain duration. It seems like if the user rides for a long period of time (beyond the typical 15-30 minutes), they are probably resting with the bike reserved for them. It is possible they are tourists. There also seem to be some rides with no travel distance but long duration; this might mean that the rider made a round trip, parking at the same station.

Conclusion¶

From this analysis, I've gained a better understanding of the Bay Wheels user base. Subscribers represent over 80% of users, most being commuters in the city. The subscribers' typical pattern include biking at 9a to arrive at work and 5p to leave work on Mondays through Fridays. Customers have lesser influence on the bike traffic, but the most customers use bikes on Saturdays.

The average trip is 15 minutes long, with stations usually no more than 4 miles apart (most are 1 mile apart). There are some people who reserve their bikes for long periods of time, but start and end at the same station. The paths with the highest amount traffic include stations along Market Street and Financial District, where most people go to work. Some other popular paths and stations are along the water on Embarcadero.
